ture Kids”, to present their struggles with identity, belonging and internalized racism in their own words. The result is the first engaging, anthropological critique of the way Western-style cosmopolitanism is institutionalized as cultural capital to reproduce global socio-cultural inequalities. From the introduction: When I first went back to high school at thirty-something, I wanted to write a book about people who live in multiple countries as children and grow up into adults addicted to migrating. I wanted to write about people like Anne-Sophie Bolon who are popularly referred to as “Third Culture Kids” or “global nomads.” … I wanted to probe the contradiction between the celebrated image of “global citizens” and the economic privilege that makes their mobile lifestyle possible. From a personal angle, I was interested in exploring the voices among this population that had yet to be heard (particularly the voices of those of Asian descent) by documenting the persistence of culture, race, and language in defining social relations even among self-proclaimed cosmopolitan youth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aEducational anthropologyzIndonesia. 0aEurocentrism. 0aInternational educationxSocial aspectszIndonesia. 0aInternational schoolszIndonesia. 0aThird-culture childrenxEducationzIndonesia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aanthropology.  acosmopolitanism.  acultural capital.  aculture and class.  aeducation.  aeurocentric.  afirst generation immigrant.  aidentity.  aimmigration.  ainternational education.  ainternational ideology.  ainternational students.  amigrants.  aserial migrants.  aserial migration.  athird culture kids.  atransnational youth.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 201